The case against Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) leader Julius Malema has been adjourned by the Newcastle Magistrate Court on Tuesday.Malema appeared briefly in court for his &#8216;land grab&#8217; statements he made in December 2014.The case is set to resume on 01 September 2017.He is accused of calling for land invasions during the EFF elective conference in Bloemfontein.He is charged with contravening the Riotous Assemblies Act for instructing members of the EFF to occupy vacant land wherever it may be found.The new charge brought against the CIC Julius Malema is on: pic.twitter.com/f3GPe0Xyhn EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) July 3, 2017The charge sheet reads: &#8220;On November 7, 2016, in Newcastle, Malema unlawfully and intentionally incited, instigated, commanded or procured his Economic Freedom Fighters and or others to commit a crime, to wit, trespass, in contravention of Section 1 (1) of the Trespass Act 6 of 1959 by illegally occupying any vacant land wherever they found some and thereby committing the crime of incitement,&#8221;&nbsp;-TNA Reporter